{
  "texts": [
    "I. INTRODUCTIONTheoretical research into the nonequilibrium dynamics of strongly-correlated quantum many-body systems continues to be fueled from several directions.",
    "First, the experimental advances with ultrafast dynamics provide access to ever-more time windows and observables, unveiling physics that has been out of reach so far [1][2][3][4][5][6][7][8][9].",
    "This includes the short-time dynamics in the electronic relaxation dynamics [5,9], stabilization of metastable states [2,8], and controlled driving of materials into states with a desired type of order [4,7].",
    "Second, modeling the relevant materials often requires accounting for several degrees of freedom, such as itinerant electrons, orbital degrees of freedom, phonons, or magnetic excitations, giving rise to a high degree of complexity [10,11].",
    "Third, theoretical descriptions face formidable challenges, since several decades in time need to be covered with different physics dominating different time windows [12][13][14]."
  ]
}